This paper proposes a novel algorithm for robust model learning in the presence of agnostic selection bias. The algorithm incorporates causal techniques into predictive modeling and uses global confounder balancing to identify causal features that are stable across domains. The paper focuses on machine learning and predictive modeling, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. Additionally, the paper mentions transfer learning, which is a common topic in the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. The use of causal techniques suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science) sub-category. The paper also conducts experiments on both synthetic and real-world datasets, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) or cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-categories. Overall, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG, followed by cs.AI, cs.CE, cs.IT, and cs.DS.
